07820nam a22009375i 9780823293377DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232933777 a10.1515/97808232933772doi  a(DE-B1597)565974  a(OCoLC)1306539732  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0050002bisacsh00aThinking in Dark Times :bHannah Arendt on Ethics and Politics /ced. by Jeffrey Katz, Roger Berkowitz, Thomas Keenan. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tPreface -- tEditors’ Note -- tIntroduction: Thinking in Dark Times -- tPart I. Politics -- tReflections on Antisemitism -- tFiction as Poison -- tA Discriminating Politics -- tHannah Arendt’s Political Engagements -- tWhat Does It Mean to Think About Politics? -- tPart II. Lying and Politics -- tA Lying World Order: Political Deception and the Threat of Totalitarianism -- tLying and History -- tPart III.Citizenship -- tThe Experience of Action -- tDissent in Dark Times: Hannah Arendt on Civil Disobedience and Constitutional Patriotism -- tPromising and Civil Disobedience: Arendt’s Political Modernism -- tPart IV. Evil and Eichmann in Jerusalem -- tIs Evil Banal? A Misleading Question -- tBanality and Cleverness: Eichmann in Jerusalem Revisited -- tJudging the Events of Our Time -- tArendt’s Banality of Evil Thesis and the Arab-Israeli Conflict -- tPart V. Judaism and Cosmopolitanism -- tLiberating the Pariah: Politics, the Jews, and Hannah Arendt -- tHannah Arendt’s Jewish Experience: Thinking, Acting, Judging -- tThe Pariah as Rebel: Hannah Arendt’s Jewish Writings -- tHannah Arendt’s Jewish Identity -- tJewish to the Core -- tPart VI. Thinking in Dark Times -- tThinking Big in Dark Times -- tCrimes of Action, Crimes of Thought: Arendt on Reconciliation, Forgiveness, and Judgment -- tSolitude and the Activity of Thinking -- tPart VII. Sites of Memory -- tExile Readings: Hannah Arendt’s Library -- tRemembering Hannah: An Interview with Jack Blum -- tMy Hannah Arendt Project -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHannah Arendt is one of the most important political theorists of the twentieth century. In her works, she grappled with the dark events of that century, probing the nature of power, authority, and evil, and seeking to confront totalitarian horrors on their own terms. This book focuses on how, against the professionalized discourses of theory, Arendt insists on the greater political importance of the ordinary activity of thinking. Indeed, she argues that the activity of thinking is the only reliable protection against the horrors that buffeted the last century. Its essays explore and enact that activity, which Arendt calls the habit of erecting obstacles to oversimplifications, compromises, and conventions. Most of the essays were written for a conference at Bard College celebrating the 100th anniversary of Arendt’s birth. Arendt left her personal library and literary effects to Bard, and she is buried in the Bard College cemetery. Material from the Bard archive—such as a postcard to Arendt from Walter Benjamin or her annotation in her copy of Machiavelli’s The Prince—and images from her life are interspersed with the essays in this volume. The volume will offer provocations and insights to Arendt scholars, students discovering Arendt’s work, and general readers attracted to Arendt’s vision of the importance of thinking in our own dark times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aAbady, Shy, econtributor.4ctb4